<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-058-082  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 058 082.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Information Week  Feb 13 1989 n207 p12(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Hidden assets: can MIS save S andamp; Ls? (management informationsystems - savings and loans)</TITLE><AUTHOR>McClatchy, Will; Pelton, Charles; Puttre, Michael.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Many believe that MIS (management information systems) will be oneof the keys to saving many savings and loans institutions fromfailure.andP;  At least one thrift executive believes that there isstill plenty of business for S andamp; Ls, but they have to gain morecontrol over their information systems.andP;  S andamp; Ls need to competewith banks if they are going to grow and prosper, and banks aresix to 10 years ahead of thrifts in MIS automation.andP;  BancFloridais one thrift that is intent on catching up with the banks.andP;  Ithas even changed its charter and plans in order to become a bank,moving beyond simple savings accounts and mortgage lending totransaction accounts and commercial real estate lending.andP;  Thethrift recently installed an online information retrieval systemthat works with microfiche in tracking customer accounts andtransaction documents.andP;  BancFlorida expects to save $100,000 ayear in paper.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     MISAutomationSavings and LoanBanking.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>